	 We use a "strict" DTD to make IE follow the alignment rules. -->
	 
<html xmlns:t="http://tapestry.apache.org/schema/tapestry_5_3.xsd">
<head>
	<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="${context:css/examples/js.css}"/>
</head>
<body>
	<h1>Robust JavaScript</h1>

	<noscript class="js-required">
		${message:javascript_required}
	</noscript> 	

	A more robust solution is to tell the Tapestry.Initializer to instantiate our JavaScript classes.
	Tapestry.Initializer runs in the browser and brings the benefit of exception catching and reporting if initialization fails.
	It also ensures things will work correctly not just in a full page render, but also during an AJAX partial page render.<br/>
	
	<div class="eg">
		<form t:type="form" t:autofocus="false">
			<input t:type="TextField" t:id="firstName" t:clientid="prop:firstNameId"/>
			<input t:type="TextField" t:id="lastName" t:clientid="prop:lastNameId"/><br/>
	 	</form>
	</div>

 	Another improvement we have made here is to ensure the client ids really are what we think they are: "firstName" and "lastName". 
 	There are situations in which the default client id can be a surprise, particularly within a Loop or a Zone.<br/><br/>
	
